 witness, memory, and melancholy.Among the sites of loss the authors revisit are slavery, apartheid, genocide, war, diaspora, migration, suicide, and disease. Their subjects range from the Irish Famine and the Ottoman slaughter of Armenians to the aftermath of the Vietnam War and apartheid in South Africa, problems of partial immigration and assimilation, AIDS, and the re-envisioning of leftist movements. In particular, Loss reveals how melancholia can lend meaning and force to notions of activism, ethics, and identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLoss (Psychology)xSocial aspects. 0aMelancholy in literature. 0aMelancholyxSocial aspects. 0aPsychic traumaxSocial aspects. 0aSocial historyy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aaids.  aanthology.  aapartheid.  aculture of grief.  adiaspora.  adisease.  aethics.  afeminists.  afilm critics.  agenocide.  agrief.  ahistory.  ahuman condition.  aidentity.  airish famine.  alife lessons.  aliterary critics.  amemory.  amigration.  amourning.  anonfiction essays.  aottoman slaughter.  aovercoming loss.  apersonal journey.  apolitical activists.  apolitical issues.  apolitical theorists.  apsychology of loss.  arealistic.  aslavery.  asocial politics.  asuicide.  atragic.  avietnam war.  awarfare.  awitness.1 aBrown, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristiansë, Yvette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooppan, Vilashini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrimp, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCvetkovich, Ann, econtributor.4